WHEN the neighbours heard the girls&rsquo; screams, they rushed to the burning shack.But there was not much they could do . . . Sinegugu (6), Sinenhlanhla (6) and Esihle Mtolo (3) burnt to death!The incident happened on Sunday morning at a squatter camp in Fannin Road in Wyebank near Pinetown, west of Durban. The girls&rsquo; madala, Simon Mtolo (56), told Daily Sun they would have survived if taps in the area had not been not dry.&ldquo;When I arrived at the scene after being called by neighbours, the flames were too strong. We couldn&rsquo;t get into the shack,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;We were running around with empty buckets. The taps were dry and the neighbours didn&rsquo;t have enough water. &ldquo;We had to run to a neighbouring area with our buckets, but it was too late.&rdquo;Simon said the water shortage in Wyebank started at the end of last year. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve never received an explanation from the authorities.&rdquo;Simon said his daughter, the kids&rsquo; mum, was not there when the fire started.&ldquo;She only arrived while we were putting out the fire,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;She&rsquo;s so shocked she can&rsquo;t explain where she was. The cause of the fire is not yet known.&rdquo;Police spokeswoman Captain Nqobile Gwala said three inquest dockets and a case of child neglect were opened at the Pinetown Police Station. &ldquo;Circumstances surrounding the incident are being investigated,&rdquo; said Gwala.Asked for comment, eThekwini spokeswoman Tozi Mthethwa assured the People&rsquo;s Paper that the municipality would investigate the matter.